n</i>), borne by the first high priest of the Israelites, the brother of Moses (Exodus 4:14). Like <i>Moses</i>, it is probably of Egyptian origin, with a meaning no longer recoverable. In England and Wales, the name comes from the occasional adoption of <i>Aaron</i> as a Christian personal name. In south Wales, for example, where fixed surnames developed much later than in England, it was coined independently as a surname in the 17th–19th centuries, reflecting the enthusiasm for Old Testament personal names among Nonconformists."]}]},{"name":"Gwenllian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>gwen</i>, the feminine form of <i>gwyn</i> ‘white, fair; blessed, holy’ (  see  Gwen  ) + <i>lliant</i> ‘flood, flow’ (probably in the transferred sense ‘foamy’ or ‘white’, referring to a pale complexion)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwenllian ARON was born about 1020, in Radnorshire, Wales as the daughter of Aaron op Poen. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Iorwerth ap Cadwgon. She died in 1121, in Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 102."},"et":{"about 1020–1121":"umbes 1020–1121","1020–1121":"1020–1121","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1040–1124":"1040–1124","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1000–Male":"1000–Surnud","about 1060":"umbes 1060","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1124":"1124","1121":"1121","1000":"1000","1020":"1020","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","about 1020":"umbes 1020","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Powys Castle, Powys, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Ceri, Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1020–1121":"noin 1020–1121","1020–1121":"1020–1121","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1040–1124":"1040–1124","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","1060–Male":"